Opposition parties and their supporters will gather at Mary Fitzgerald Square on Monday at 8am before heading to the Constitutional Court to support the secret ballot bid. JOHANNESBURG - Opposition Parties have called on South Africans to show a united front by marching to the Constitutional Court on Monday, where the case involving the vote of no confidence in President Jacob Zuma will be heard.Zuma and National Assembly Speaker Baleka Mbete are challenging the United Democratic Movement s (UDM) interpretation of the Constitution.The UDM wants the vote to be held by secret ballot in Parliament.The African Christian Democratic Party s Kenneth Meshoe says president Zuma was elected as president through a secret ballot and should therefore go out in the same way. We are not happy with the direction this country is taking. UDM leader Bantu Holomisa says the country has a duty to hold the president to account. We pay your salary and voted for you. Put the interest of your party first before the interest of your party or bosses. Opposition parties and their supporters will gather at Mary Fitzgerald Square on Monday at 8am before heading to the Constitutional Court to support the secret ballot bid.(Edited by Shimoney Regter)